<div id="review_579708434" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/579708434" />
    <a title="Somekindofnobody" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/135885-somekindofnobody"><img alt="Somekindofnobody" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1386079175p2/135885.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/579708434?book_show_action=true">Apr 03, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Somekindofnobody" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Somekindofnobody" href="/user/show/135885-somekindofnobody">Somekindofnobody</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780957029" href="/book/show/17571081-aimee-and-the-bear">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer579708434" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5619876901603567669">Did you know that gargoyles ride the perimeter of Night School? Did you know that Barnaby the bear can get into your dreams? Where did that line of reality go???? Because its not here. What a fascinating read!! This is, hands down, one of the best books I&apos;ve found in years. Like I said, Wow. No matter what I render as a review, there is nothing left more important than WOW. This author just blew me away with the perfect clarity, perfect flow, perfectly satisfying writing style that made me smile</span>
  <span id="freeText5619876901603567669" style="display:none">Did you know that gargoyles ride the perimeter of Night School? Did you know that Barnaby the bear can get into your dreams? Where did that line of reality go???? Because its not here. What a fascinating read!! This is, hands down, one of the best books I've found in years. Like I said, Wow. No matter what I render as a review, there is nothing left more important than WOW. This author just blew me away with the perfect clarity, perfect flow, perfectly satisfying writing style that made me smile or frown out loud at times. I may have said this before, but this time I mean it when I say that I was captivated from the first 4 paragraphs. In fact, with each additional paragraph in chapter one the book became less like a book and more like a movie in my mind. I have NEVER had that literally happen before. As Amy nonchalantly mouths the words to the movie I can see her body, the room, her actions...everything. I see it.<br /><br />Written so well that I can compare it to Pans Labyrinth where the line between reality and fantasy is hidden so well that you eventually don't even bother to look for it. And, the subtitles (words) disappear as you fall into a rich and vibrant pseudo reality and drown in it. Willingly.<br /><br />Because I recently watched the movie Suckerpunch, I was able to retain that dark atmosphere when reading this. It is strange but realistic. I had to wonder right away whether or not Amy was actually seeing the things in her mind or just imagining. With such great storytelling all you can do is see what you see and only wish to be able to get into the character's head. It is a great storyteller who can make their reader crave to meet their creations in real life. To make their readers want to see more inside the mind of their creation.<br /><br />Right away, you can't help but to be bonded to precious little Amy, whom is being abused by her mother. Obviously heartbroken beyond repair over being left by her husband, the mother takes her bitterness out on his spawn. In her anger the mother forgets that it is her daughter, rather she sees Amy as 'his' daughter and takes her wrath out on the child. She is sarcastic and scorns the child often which leads me right away to believe that the mother fears the same rejection from the child and that is infuriating. The scorn quickly becomes physical...meaning that there is abuse.<br /><br />If I could mix Suckerpunch with Wizard of Oz, perhaps I'd have such a concoction as Aimee and the Bear. I call her Amy because that is her name in this world. In the Other Place she is known as Aimee and she takes her bear, Barnaby, by the hand and travels there where the witch lives. I laughed out loud as they entered the grove to Pooh Bears House and Barnaby got jealous and threatened to eat her hand off (just to prove he was NOT a jolly old silly type bear like Pooh!).<br /><br />(I'm copying this from the first or second chapter because Barnaby RULES)<br />(about to enter Pooh Bears House) Barnaby continued, "-and he never remembers anything you say. He's like a goldfish. Oh there's a jar of honey!...I forgot it was there!...Oh there's a jar of honey!...idiot. I hope Piglet's there. Do you hear me little girl? I hope Piglet's visiting. Do you have any applesauce, little girl?"(end)<br /><br />Just as you think you are reading a book there is a pause. Someone suddenly talking to you...whispering to you in your head. You will have to read it to see what I mean. It's a tad creepy because at first I thought it was simply the author talking to me but you realize that its the bear. Its talking to you like it does to Amy...and if you close your eyes you can see it like Aimee.<br /><br />I felt awful for the people whom held relationships with Mum. What a witch. Towards the middle-end as she belittled Uncle Chris I wanted to reach into the book and smack her sarcastic fanny! Grrrrr. You'll follow Mum's life as well as her relationships, including the one with Amy's younger brother, as the story progresses.<br /><br />This review is nothing but a half-witted remark to what is a majestically written story. Every paragraph danced and it was one of those WOW books. All I can do at this point is urge you to read the free sample and take a glimpse at what can only be described as EPIC.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5619876901603567669" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


