<div id="review_598645898" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/598645898" />
    <a title="Maree Kimberley" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5271330-maree-kimberley"><img alt="Maree Kimberley" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1602997508p2/5271330.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/598645898?book_show_action=true">Apr 24, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Maree Kimberley" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Maree Kimberley" href="/user/show/5271330-maree-kimberley">Maree Kimberley</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780957029" href="/book/show/17571081-aimee-and-the-bear">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer598645898" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10521990825419295382">This debut novel by Toby Stone is published by Hic Dragones, a UK based indie publisher (among other things) that specialises in dark fiction, the weird, and the strange. Well, Aimee and the Bear is all that and more. <br/><br/>It&apos;s a difficult book to review in that outlining the basic storyline doesn&apos;t really describe what the story is about, or how it works. In some ways, this is as realistic as fiction can get in its portrayal of a young girl who escapes into her own mind because she can&apos;t deal with t</span>
  <span id="freeText10521990825419295382" style="display:none">This debut novel by Toby Stone is published by Hic Dragones, a UK based indie publisher (among other things) that specialises in dark fiction, the weird, and the strange. Well, Aimee and the Bear is all that and more. <br /><br />It's a difficult book to review in that outlining the basic storyline doesn't really describe what the story is about, or how it works. In some ways, this is as realistic as fiction can get in its portrayal of a young girl who escapes into her own mind because she can't deal with the horrible reality of her day to day life. It's also a classic 'hero's journey' story (or in this case, heroine's journey) as Amy/Aimee struggles to save her little brother from the life they have been unfortunate enough to be born into. With elements of horror and dark fairytale, Stone's novel takes us with Amy/Aimee and her bear as she struggles to defeat the evil in her 'real' and 'imaginary' lives.<br /><br />This is a book that lingers. Although I found some passages of writing a little convoluted there are also scenes so vivid in their portrayal of the cruelty that adults can inflict upon children that it is heartbreaking. Yet despite the hardships and the horror that Amy is forced to suffer, as Aimee, her alter ego in her imaginary world, she continues to fight to save her brother, long after she has realised she cannot save herself.<br /><br />Dark, strange, confronting and thoughtful, this is a book that deserves a wide readership. Highly recommended.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10521990825419295382" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


